    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Big-Omega Notation Demonstration</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            margin: 20px;\n            background-color: #f4f4f4;\n        }\n        h1 {\n            color: #333;\n        }\n        .description {\n            margin: 20px 0;\n        }\n        .code {\n            background: #fff;\n            border: 1px solid #ddd;\n            padding: 10px;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            font-family: monospace;\n        }\n        #result {\n            margin-top: 20px;\n            font-weight: bold;\n            color: #007bff;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n    <h1>Big-Omega Notation Demonstration</h1>\n    <div class=\"description\">\n        <p>\n            Big-Omega notation (Ω) provides a lower bound for the runtime of an algorithm.\n            It describes the best-case scenario for the growth rate of an algorithm's runtime.\n            Below is an example demonstrating Big-Omega notation through a simple algorithm.\n        </p>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"code\">\n        <strong>JavaScript Function:</strong>\n        <pre id=\"codeSnippet\">\nfunction findMin(array) {\n    if (array.length === 0) return null; // Ω(1) - constant time for empty array\n    let min = array[0];\n    for (let i = 1; i < array.length; i++) {\n        if (array[i] < min) {\n            min = array[i];\n        }\n    }\n    return min; // Ω(n) - linear time in the worst case\n}\n        </pre>\n    </div>\n\n    <button id=\"runCode\">Run Code</button>\n    <div id=\"result\"></div>\n\n    <script>\n        function findMin(array) {\n            if (array.length === 0) return null; // Ω(1) - constant time for empty array\n            let min = array[0];\n            for (let i = 1; i < array.length; i++) {\n                if (array[i] < min) {\n                    min = array[i];\n                }\n            }\n            return min; // Ω(n) - linear time in the worst case\n        }\n\n        document.getElementById('runCode').addEventListener('click', function() {\n            const array = [5, 3, 8, 1, 2, 7];\n            const min = findMin(array);\n            document.getElementById('result').innerText = `The minimum value in the array [${array}] is: ${min}`;\n        });\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
